
[1]random

   RAN'DOM, n.

   1. A roving motion or course without direction; hence, want of
   direction, rule or method; hazard; chance; used in the phrase, at
   random, that is, without a settled point of direction; at hazard.

   2. Course; motion; progression; distance of a body thrown; as the
   furthest random of a missile weapon.

                                 RAN'DOM, a.

   1. Done at hazard or without settled aim or purpose; left to chance; as
   a random blow.

   2. Uttered or done without previous calculation; as a random guess.
